1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Group chats during a live event are noise.

2
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:11,300
By the time someone reads a message and

3
00:00:11,600 --> 00:00:13,600
replies, the moment has passed.

4
00:00:13,900 --> 00:00:16,150
CueDeck's broadcast bar solves this —

5
00:00:16,450 --> 00:00:19,075
one message, every connected device, zero round-trips.

6
00:00:19,375 --> 00:00:23,125
The broadcast bar sits at the top of the console.

7
00:00:23,425 --> 00:00:25,675
Directors type a message, hit send,

8
00:00:25,975 --> 00:00:29,350
and it appears immediately across all connected devices —

9
00:00:29,650 --> 00:00:31,900
every stage manager, every AV engineer,

10
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:36,325
every interpretation booth — as a coloured overlay they can't miss.

11
00:00:36,625 --> 00:00:39,250
Messages dismiss when each person taps them.

12
00:00:39,550 --> 00:00:42,175
The director can see who's cleared it.

13
00:00:42,475 --> 00:00:45,475
It's not a chat — it's a command.

14
00:00:45,775 --> 00:00:47,775
Let's send one.

15
00:00:48,075 --> 00:00:50,075
Click the broadcast bar.

16
00:00:50,375 --> 00:00:54,500
Type your message — 'Delay 5 minutes — hold all transitions'.

17
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:56,800
There's a character counter.

18
00:00:57,100 --> 00:00:59,350
Keep it short and punchy —

19
00:00:59,650 --> 00:01:01,650
this is a live environment.

20
00:01:01,950 --> 00:01:03,950
Hit Send.

21
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:06,250
Watch.

22
00:01:06,550 --> 00:01:08,550
Boom.

23
00:01:08,850 --> 00:01:11,100
Every connected role sees it instantly.

24
00:01:11,400 --> 00:01:16,275
The banner sits at the top of their view until they dismiss it.

25
00:01:16,575 --> 00:01:19,200
They can't accidentally miss it scrolling past.

26
00:01:19,500 --> 00:01:22,125
For common situations you'll use over and

27
00:01:22,425 --> 00:01:24,425
over, CueDeck has broadcast presets.

28
00:01:24,725 --> 00:01:26,975
One click — no typing needed.

29
00:01:27,275 --> 00:01:30,275
'HOLD — Do not proceed.' Great for when

30
00:01:30,575 --> 00:01:33,200
you need everything to pause right now.

31
00:01:33,500 --> 00:01:35,500
'Speakers to stage immediately.' Self-explanatory.

32
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:39,550
'Running 5 minutes late — adjust your clocks.' The director

33
00:01:39,850 --> 00:01:43,225
can customise these presets for each event in advance.

34
00:01:43,525 --> 00:01:46,150
We'll show that in the signage episode.

35
00:01:46,450 --> 00:01:49,825
Each person dismisses the message on their own device.

36
00:01:50,125 --> 00:01:53,125
The director doesn't need to clear it globally.

37
00:01:53,425 --> 00:01:57,175
Local dismiss means everyone works at their own pace once

38
00:01:57,475 --> 00:01:59,475
they've acknowledged the instruction.

39
00:01:59,775 --> 00:02:03,525
The broadcast stays visible until dismissed — it doesn't auto-fade.

40
00:02:03,825 --> 00:02:05,825
Clear, instant, impossible to miss.

41
00:02:06,125 --> 00:02:08,125
That's the broadcast bar.

42
00:02:08,425 --> 00:02:10,425
Next episode — delay management.

43
00:02:10,725 --> 00:02:13,725
What happens when a session runs long and

44
00:02:14,025 --> 00:02:17,775
you need to cascade a delay through the rest of

45
00:02:18,075 --> 00:02:20,325
the programme without losing your mind.

46
00:02:20,625 --> 00:02:22,625
See you in episode six.
